1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,730
- Mathematics began as a
way to quantify our world,
数学这一学科
2
00:00:03,730 --> 00:00:04,910
to measure land,
起源于对世界的量化
3
00:00:04,910 --> 00:00:08,480
predict the motions of planets,
and keep track of commerce.
测量土地、预测行星运动、记录交易
4
00:00:08,480 --> 00:00:11,590
Then came a problem considered impossible.
后来，一个看似无解的问题出现了
5
00:00:11,590 --> 00:00:14,450
The secret to solving
it was to separate math
而解决这个问题的关键
6
00:00:14,450 --> 00:00:18,220
from the real world, to
split algebra from geometry
就是把真实世界和代数、几何分开
7
00:00:18,220 --> 00:00:20,840
and to invent new numbers so fanciful
然后整出一种奇妙的数
8
00:00:20,840 --> 00:00:23,020
they are called imaginary.
称为虚数
9
00:00:23,020 --> 00:00:26,750
Ironically, 400 years later,
these very numbers turn up
讽刺的是，虚数在四百年后
10
00:00:26,750 --> 00:00:30,400
in the heart of our best
physical theory of the universe.
成为了世界上最美妙的物理理论的核心
11
00:00:30,400 --> 00:00:33,940
Only by abandoning math's
connection to reality
而物理世界的这一本质
12
00:00:33,940 --> 00:00:36,956
could we discover reality's true nature.
只有断开数学和现实联系才能发现
13
00:00:36,956 --> 00:00:38,720
(light music)
（嘤乐）
14
00:00:38,720 --> 00:00:41,290
In 1494, Luca Pacioli
在 1494，达芬奇的数学老师

15
00:00:41,290 --> 00:00:44,197
who is Leonardo da Vinci's
math teacher publishes
卢卡·帕丘利发布了名为

16
00:00:44,197 --> 00:00:47,560
"Summa de Arithmetica,"
a comprehensive summary
"Summa de Artihmetica" 的著作

17
00:00:47,560 --> 00:00:51,230
of all mathematics known in
Renaissance Italy at the time.
总结了意大利文艺复兴时期的所有数学知识

18
00:00:51,230 --> 00:00:53,380
In it, there's a section on the cubic,
里面有一节记载三次方程相关的内容

19
00:00:53,380 --> 00:00:56,370
any equation which today
we would write as ax cubed
也就是我们现如今写成

20
00:00:56,370 --> 00:01:00,200
plus bx squared plus
cx plus d equals zero.
ax^3+bx^2+cx+d=0 形式的方程

21
00:01:00,200 --> 00:01:02,550
People have been trying
to find a general solution
当时的人们

22
00:01:02,550 --> 00:01:05,630
to the cubic for at least 4,000 years,
已经找了 4000 年这种方程的通解

23
00:01:05,630 --> 00:01:08,100
but each ancient civilization
that encountered it,
但是各个文明碰上它

24
00:01:08,100 --> 00:01:10,430
the Babylonians, Greeks, Chinese,
不论是巴比伦、希腊、华夏

25
00:01:10,430 --> 00:01:12,740
Indians, Egyptians, and Persians,
印度、希腊还是波斯文明

26
00:01:12,740 --> 00:01:15,380
they all came up empty-handed.
都对此束手无策

27
00:01:15,380 --> 00:01:17,990
Pacioli's conclusion is that a solution
帕丘利对此的总结是

28
00:01:17,990 --> 00:01:21,410
to the cubic equation is impossible.
三次方程没有通解

29
00:01:21,410 --> 00:01:23,370
Now, this should be at
least a little surprising,
这种想法或许有些让人意外

30
00:01:23,370 --> 00:01:25,130
since without the X cubed term,
因为去掉三次项

31
00:01:25,130 --> 00:01:27,200
the equation is simply a quadratic.
这就只是个二次方程

32
00:01:27,200 --> 00:01:29,310
And many ancient civilizations
而许多古代文明

33
00:01:29,310 --> 00:01:32,620
had solved quadratics
thousands of years earlier.
几千年前就会解二次方程了

34
00:01:32,620 --> 00:01:34,610
Today, anyone who's passed eighth grade
而在现如今

35
00:01:34,610 --> 00:01:36,260
knows the general solution.
一个初二的学生都知道通解是

36
00:01:36,260 --> 00:01:39,340
It's minus b plus minus
root b squared minus four ac
(-b ± √(b^2-4ac))/2a

37
00:01:39,340 --> 00:01:41,170
all over two a.

38
00:01:41,170 --> 00:01:44,250
But most people just plug
and chug into this formula
但是许多人只是会套这个公式

39
00:01:44,250 --> 00:01:46,840
completely oblivious to the geometry
而完全忽略了古代数学家推导时

40
00:01:46,840 --> 00:01:50,320
that ancient mathematicians
used to derive it.
背后运用的几何

41
00:01:50,320 --> 00:01:52,080
You know, back in those days,
因为在那时候

42
00:01:52,080 --> 00:01:54,810
mathematics wasn't
written down in equations.
数学家不用式子

43
00:01:54,810 --> 00:01:58,220
It was written with words and pictures.
而是用文字和图像描述

44
00:01:58,220 --> 00:01:59,053
Take, for example,
例如 x^2+26x=27

45
00:01:59,053 --> 00:02:03,050
the equation x squared plus 26x equals 27.

46
00:02:03,050 --> 00:02:06,480
Ancient mathematicians would
think of the x squared term
古代的数学家

47
00:02:06,480 --> 00:02:10,980
like a literal square
with sides of length x.
把 x^2 当作一个边长为 x 的正方形

48
00:02:10,980 --> 00:02:12,670
And then 26x,
而 26x 则是一个

49
00:02:12,670 --> 00:02:17,010
well, that would be a rectangle
with one side of length 26
一边长为 26

50
00:02:17,010 --> 00:02:19,780
and the other side of length x,
另一边长为 x 的矩形

51
00:02:19,780 --> 00:02:24,430
and these two areas together add to 27.
这俩的面积和为 27

52
00:02:24,430 --> 00:02:26,880
So how do we figure out what x is?
那怎么求出 x 呢？

53
00:02:26,880 --> 00:02:31,880
Well, we can take this 26x
rectangle and cut it in half.
我们把这个 26x 的矩形切成两半

54
00:02:33,290 --> 00:02:38,230
So now I have two 13x rectangles
and I can position them
就得到了两个 13x 的矩形

55
00:02:38,230 --> 00:02:41,420
so the new shape I create
is almost a square,
然后我把它摆成这样

56
00:02:41,420 --> 00:02:44,250
It's just missing this section down here.
就是少了一块的正方形

57
00:02:44,250 --> 00:02:46,160
But I know the dimensions of this section.
但是我知道少的这块的尺寸

58
00:02:46,160 --> 00:02:48,450
It's just 13 by 13.
是 13 x 13

59
00:02:48,450 --> 00:02:52,410
So I can complete the square by adding in
那我就可以给它补上这样一个

60
00:02:52,410 --> 00:02:55,970
a 13 by 13 square.
13 x 13 的正方形

61
00:02:55,970 --> 00:02:57,860
Now, since I've added 13-squared
那现在我在式子左边多了 13^2

62
00:02:57,860 --> 00:03:01,450
or 169 to the left-hand
side of the equation,
也就是 169

63
00:03:01,450 --> 00:03:03,480
I also have to add 169
我要在式子右边也多 169

64
00:03:03,480 --> 00:03:05,980
to the right-hand side of the equation

65
00:03:05,980 --> 00:03:07,670
to maintain the equality.
才能保持两边相等

66
00:03:07,670 --> 00:03:09,640
So now I have this larger square
现在我的大正方形

67
00:03:09,640 --> 00:03:13,917
with sides of length X plus
13, and it is equal to 196.
边长是 (13+x)，面积是 196

68
00:03:16,470 --> 00:03:19,700
Now the square root of 196 is 14.
196 开方得 14

69
00:03:19,700 --> 00:03:23,330
So I know that the sides of
this square have length 14,
所以我就知道这个正方形边长是 14

70
00:03:23,330 --> 00:03:26,820
which means X is equal to one.
也就意味着 X=1

71
00:03:26,820 --> 00:03:29,870
Now this is a great visual way

72
00:03:29,870 --> 00:03:34,870
to solve a quadratic equation,
but it isn't complete.

73
00:03:34,910 --> 00:03:37,080
I mean, if you look at
our original equation,

74
00:03:37,080 --> 00:03:39,820
x equals one is a solution.

75
00:03:39,820 --> 00:03:42,960
But so is negative 27.

76
00:03:42,960 --> 00:03:46,620
For thousands of years,
mathematicians were oblivious

77
00:03:46,620 --> 00:03:49,430
to the negative solutions
to their equations

78
00:03:49,430 --> 00:03:52,020
because they were dealing
with things in the real world,

79
00:03:52,020 --> 00:03:54,130
lengths and areas and volumes.

80
00:03:54,130 --> 00:03:56,650
I mean, what would it
mean to have a square

81
00:03:56,650 --> 00:03:59,590
with sides of length negative 27?

82
00:03:59,590 --> 00:04:02,080
That just doesn't make any sense.

83
00:04:02,080 --> 00:04:06,360
So for those mathematicians,
negative numbers didn't exist.

84
00:04:06,360 --> 00:04:07,320
You could subtract,

85
00:04:07,320 --> 00:04:09,930
that is find the difference
between two positive quantities,

86
00:04:09,930 --> 00:04:11,740
but you couldn't have a negative answer

87
00:04:11,740 --> 00:04:13,630
or negative coefficients.

88
00:04:13,630 --> 00:04:15,960
Mathematicians were so
averse to negative numbers

89
00:04:15,960 --> 00:04:19,540
that there was no single
quadratic equation.

90
00:04:19,540 --> 00:04:21,880
Instead, there were six different versions

91
00:04:21,880 --> 00:04:25,820
arranged so that the coefficients
were always positive.

92
00:04:25,820 --> 00:04:28,350
The same approach was
taken with the cubic.

93
00:04:28,350 --> 00:04:31,750
In the 11th century, Persian
mathematician Omar Khayyam

94
00:04:31,750 --> 00:04:34,800
identified 19 different cubic equations,

95
00:04:34,800 --> 00:04:37,610
again, keeping all coefficients positive.

96
00:04:37,610 --> 00:04:39,680
He found numerical
solutions to some of them

97
00:04:39,680 --> 00:04:41,770
by considering the
intersections of shapes,

98
00:04:41,770 --> 00:04:43,960
like hyperbolas and circles,

99
00:04:43,960 --> 00:04:46,210
but he fell short of his ultimate goal,

100
00:04:46,210 --> 00:04:48,510
a general solution to the cubic.

101
00:04:48,510 --> 00:04:51,100
He wrote, "Maybe one of
those who will come after us

102
00:04:51,100 --> 00:04:53,490
will succeed in finding it."

103
00:04:53,490 --> 00:04:56,230
400 years later and 4,000 kilometers away,

104
00:04:56,230 --> 00:05:00,550
the solution begins to take shape.

105
00:05:00,550 --> 00:05:03,090
Scipione del Ferro is
a mathematics professor

106
00:05:03,090 --> 00:05:04,653
at the University of Bologna.

107
00:05:05,500 --> 00:05:07,280
Sometime around 1510,

108
00:05:07,280 --> 00:05:11,610
he finds a method to reliably
solve depressed cubics.

109
00:05:11,610 --> 00:05:13,680
These are a subset of cubic equations

110
00:05:13,680 --> 00:05:16,140
with no X squared term.

111
00:05:16,140 --> 00:05:18,210
So what does he do after solving a problem

112
00:05:18,210 --> 00:05:20,370
that has stumped
mathematicians from millennia?

113
00:05:20,370 --> 00:05:21,890
One considered impossible

114
00:05:21,890 --> 00:05:24,283
by Leonardo da Vinci's math teacher?

115
00:05:25,340 --> 00:05:28,100
He tells no one.

116
00:05:28,100 --> 00:05:31,450
See, being a mathematician
in the 1500s is hard.

117
00:05:31,450 --> 00:05:33,280
Your job is constantly under threat

118
00:05:33,280 --> 00:05:36,220
from other mathematicians
who can show up at any time

119
00:05:36,220 --> 00:05:38,460
and challenge you for your position.

120
00:05:38,460 --> 00:05:41,110
You can think of it like a math duel.

121
00:05:41,110 --> 00:05:44,140
Each participant submits a
set of questions to the other,

122
00:05:44,140 --> 00:05:47,010
and the person who solves
the most questions correctly

123
00:05:47,010 --> 00:05:51,293
gets the job while the loser
suffers public humiliation.

124
00:05:52,170 --> 00:05:53,960
As far as del Ferro knows,

125
00:05:53,960 --> 00:05:57,260
no one else in the world can
solve the depressed cubic.

126
00:05:57,260 --> 00:05:59,500
So by keeping his solutions secret,

127
00:05:59,500 --> 00:06:02,520
he guarantees his own job security.

128
00:06:02,520 --> 00:06:06,580
For nearly two decades,
del Ferro keeps his secret.

129
00:06:06,580 --> 00:06:09,050
Only on his deathbed in 1526

130
00:06:09,050 --> 00:06:13,237
does he let it slip to
his student Antonio Fior.

131
00:06:13,237 --> 00:06:16,100
Fior is not as talented a
mathematician as his mentor,

132
00:06:16,100 --> 00:06:18,380
but he is young and ambitious.

133
00:06:18,380 --> 00:06:19,680
And after del Ferro's death,

134
00:06:19,680 --> 00:06:22,120
he boasts about his own
mathematical prowess

135
00:06:22,120 --> 00:06:26,190
and specifically, his ability
to solve the depressed cubic.

136
00:06:26,190 --> 00:06:28,486
On February 12, 1535,

137
00:06:28,486 --> 00:06:32,360
Fior challenges mathematician
Niccolo Fontana Tartaglia

138
00:06:32,360 --> 00:06:36,110
who has recently moved to
Fior's hometown of Venice.

139
00:06:36,110 --> 00:06:39,580
Niccolo Fontana is no
stranger to adversity.

140
00:06:39,580 --> 00:06:42,870
As a kid, his face was cut
open by a French soldier,

141
00:06:42,870 --> 00:06:44,770
leaving him with a stutter.

142
00:06:44,770 --> 00:06:46,690
That's why he's known as Tartaglia,

143
00:06:46,690 --> 00:06:49,260
which means stutterer in Italian.

144
00:06:49,260 --> 00:06:52,630
Growing up in poverty, Tartaglia
is largely self-taught.

145
00:06:52,630 --> 00:06:54,910
He claws his way up
through Italian society

146
00:06:54,910 --> 00:06:57,740
to become a respected mathematician.

147
00:06:57,740 --> 00:07:00,980
Now, all of that is at stake.

148
00:07:00,980 --> 00:07:03,450
As is the custom, in the
challenge Tartaglia gives

149
00:07:03,450 --> 00:07:06,830
a very discernment of 30 problems to Fior.

150
00:07:06,830 --> 00:07:09,630
Fior gives 30 problems to Tartaglia,

151
00:07:09,630 --> 00:07:12,093
all of which are depressed cubics.

152
00:07:13,080 --> 00:07:14,810
Each mathematician has 40 days

153
00:07:14,810 --> 00:07:17,369
to solve the 30 problems
they've been given.

154
00:07:17,369 --> 00:07:21,250
Fior can't solve a single problem.

155
00:07:21,250 --> 00:07:24,800
Tartaglia solves all 30
of Fior's depressed cubics

156
00:07:24,800 --> 00:07:26,800
in just two hours.

157
00:07:26,800 --> 00:07:30,360
It seems Fior's boastfulness
was his undoing.

158
00:07:30,360 --> 00:07:32,820
Before the challenge
came, Tartaglia learns

159
00:07:32,820 --> 00:07:35,130
that Fior's claimed to have
solved the depressed cubic,

160
00:07:35,130 --> 00:07:36,617
but he's skeptical.

161
00:07:36,617 --> 00:07:38,110
"I did not deem him capable

162
00:07:38,110 --> 00:07:41,230
of finding such a rule on
his own," Tartaglia writes.

163
00:07:41,230 --> 00:07:43,020
But word was that a great mathematician

164
00:07:43,020 --> 00:07:46,710
had revealed the secret to Fior,
which seems more plausible.

165
00:07:46,710 --> 00:07:47,820
So with the knowledge

166
00:07:47,820 --> 00:07:50,090
that a solution to the cubic is possible,

167
00:07:50,090 --> 00:07:52,170
and with his livelihood on the line,

168
00:07:52,170 --> 00:07:56,070
Tartaglia sets about solving
the depressed cubic himself.

169
00:07:56,070 --> 00:07:58,600
To do it, he extends the idea

170
00:07:58,600 --> 00:08:02,610
of completing the square
into three dimensions.

171
00:08:02,610 --> 00:08:07,090
Take the equation x cubed
plus nine x equals 26.

172
00:08:07,090 --> 00:08:10,090
You can think of x cubed
as the volume of a cube

173
00:08:10,090 --> 00:08:11,860
with sides of length x.

174
00:08:11,860 --> 00:08:15,540
And if you add a volume
of nine x, you get 26.

175
00:08:15,540 --> 00:08:17,460
So just like with completing the square,

176
00:08:17,460 --> 00:08:19,440
we need to add onto the cube

177
00:08:19,440 --> 00:08:22,690
to increase its volume by nine x.

178
00:08:22,690 --> 00:08:27,270
Imagine extending three sides
of this cube out a distance y,

179
00:08:27,270 --> 00:08:31,920
creating a new, larger cube
with sides of length, call it z.

180
00:08:31,920 --> 00:08:34,680
z is just x plus y.

181
00:08:34,680 --> 00:08:36,900
The original cube has been padded out

182
00:08:36,900 --> 00:08:41,200
and we can break up the additional
volume into seven shapes.

183
00:08:41,200 --> 00:08:43,220
There are three rectangular prisms

184
00:08:43,220 --> 00:08:46,710
with dimensions of x by x by y,

185
00:08:46,710 --> 00:08:48,700
and another three narrower prisms

186
00:08:48,700 --> 00:08:51,820
with dimensions of x by y by y,

187
00:08:51,820 --> 00:08:54,890
plus there's a cube with a volume y cubed.

188
00:08:54,890 --> 00:08:58,080
Tartaglia rearranges the
six rectangular prisms

189
00:08:58,080 --> 00:08:59,720
into one block.

190
00:08:59,720 --> 00:09:02,010
One side has length three y,

191
00:09:02,010 --> 00:09:05,280
the other has a length
x plus y, which is z,

192
00:09:05,280 --> 00:09:07,400
and the height is x.

193
00:09:07,400 --> 00:09:08,840
So the volume of this shape

194
00:09:08,840 --> 00:09:12,490
is its base, three yz times its height, x.

195
00:09:12,490 --> 00:09:16,010
And Tartaglia realizes this
volume can perfectly represent

196
00:09:16,010 --> 00:09:18,180
the nine x term in the equation,

197
00:09:18,180 --> 00:09:20,830
if its base is equal to nine.

198
00:09:20,830 --> 00:09:24,057
So he sets three yz equals nine.

199
00:09:24,057 --> 00:09:26,230
Putting the cube back together,

200
00:09:26,230 --> 00:09:29,380
you find we're missing the
one small y cubed block,

201
00:09:29,380 --> 00:09:32,090
so we can complete the cube

202
00:09:32,090 --> 00:09:35,340
by adding y cubed to both
sides of the equation.

203
00:09:35,340 --> 00:09:38,320
Now we have z cubed, the
complete larger cube,

204
00:09:38,320 --> 00:09:40,650
equals 26 plus y cubed.

205
00:09:40,650 --> 00:09:43,900
We have two equations and two unknowns.

206
00:09:43,900 --> 00:09:45,520
Solving the first equation for z

207
00:09:45,520 --> 00:09:47,140
and substituting into the second,

208
00:09:47,140 --> 00:09:51,830
we get y to the six plus
26 y cubed equals 27.

209
00:09:51,830 --> 00:09:54,670
At first glance, it seems
like we're now worse off

210
00:09:54,670 --> 00:09:55,770
than when we started.

211
00:09:55,770 --> 00:09:57,890
The variable is now raised
to the power of six,

212
00:09:57,890 --> 00:09:59,490
instead of just three.

213
00:09:59,490 --> 00:10:02,990
However, if you think of
y cubed as a new variable,

214
00:10:02,990 --> 00:10:06,040
the equation is actually a quadratic,

215
00:10:06,040 --> 00:10:09,780
the same quadratic that we
solved by completing the square.

216
00:10:09,780 --> 00:10:12,330
So we know y cubed equals one,

217
00:10:12,330 --> 00:10:16,340
which means y equals one,
and z equals three over y,

218
00:10:16,340 --> 00:10:17,900
so z is three.

219
00:10:17,900 --> 00:10:21,963
And since x plus y equals
z, x must be equal to two,

220
00:10:22,840 --> 00:10:26,440
which is indeed, a solution
to the original equation.

221
00:10:26,440 --> 00:10:27,280
And with that,

222
00:10:27,280 --> 00:10:30,030
Tartaglia becomes the
second human on the planet

223
00:10:30,030 --> 00:10:32,270
to solve the depressed cubic.

224
