To save himself the work of
going through the geometry

225
00:10:34,590 --> 00:10:36,840
for each new cubic he encounters,

226
00:10:36,840 --> 00:10:39,880
Tartaglia summarizes his
method in an algorithm,

227
00:10:39,880 --> 00:10:41,680
a set of instructions.

228
00:10:41,680 --> 00:10:44,350
He writes this down not
as a set of equations

229
00:10:44,350 --> 00:10:45,390
like we would today.

230
00:10:45,390 --> 00:10:47,440
Modern algebraic notation wouldn't exist

231
00:10:47,440 --> 00:10:50,913
for another hundred years,
but instead, as a poem.

232
00:10:52,369 --> 00:10:55,830
Tartaglia's victory makes
him something of a celebrity.

233
00:10:55,830 --> 00:10:57,760
Mathematicians are desperate to learn

234
00:10:57,760 --> 00:10:59,170
how he solved the cubic,

235
00:10:59,170 --> 00:11:03,640
especially Gerolamo Cardano,
a polymath based in Milan.

236
00:11:03,640 --> 00:11:06,310
As you can guess, Tartaglia
will have none of it.

237
00:11:06,310 --> 00:11:07,550
He refuses to reveal

238
00:11:07,550 --> 00:11:10,310
even a single question
from the competition.

239
00:11:10,310 --> 00:11:12,290
But Cardano is persistent.

240
00:11:12,290 --> 00:11:14,420
He writes a series of
letters that alternate

241
00:11:14,420 --> 00:11:17,830
between flattery and aggressive attacks.

242
00:11:17,830 --> 00:11:20,110
Eventually with the
promise of an introduction

243
00:11:20,110 --> 00:11:21,800
to his wealthy benefactor,

244
00:11:21,800 --> 00:11:25,490
Cardono manages to lure
Tartaglia to Milan.

245
00:11:25,490 --> 00:11:30,300
And there on March 25, 1539
Tartaglia reveals his method,

246
00:11:30,300 --> 00:11:34,210
but only after forcing
Cardono to swear a solemn oath

247
00:11:34,210 --> 00:11:35,940
not to tell anyone the method,

248
00:11:35,940 --> 00:11:39,670
not to publish it, and to
write it only in cipher.

249
00:11:39,670 --> 00:11:42,240
Quote, "So that after my death,

250
00:11:42,240 --> 00:11:45,300
no one shall be able to understand it."

251
00:11:45,300 --> 00:11:48,640
Cardono is delighted and
immediately starts playing around

252
00:11:48,640 --> 00:11:50,470
with Tartaglia's algorithm.

253
00:11:50,470 --> 00:11:52,740
But he has a loftier goal in mind,

254
00:11:52,740 --> 00:11:54,930
a solution to the full cubic equation,

255
00:11:54,930 --> 00:11:57,050
including the x squared term.

256
00:11:57,050 --> 00:11:59,760
And amazingly, he discovers it.

257
00:11:59,760 --> 00:12:01,700
If you substitute for x,

258
00:12:01,700 --> 00:12:04,060
x minus b over three a,

259
00:12:04,060 --> 00:12:07,270
then all the X squared terms cancel out.

260
00:12:07,270 --> 00:12:10,200
This is the way to turn
any general cubic equation

261
00:12:10,200 --> 00:12:11,880
into a depressed cubic,

262
00:12:11,880 --> 00:12:15,000
which can then be solved
by Tartaglia's formula.

263
00:12:15,000 --> 00:12:17,570
Cardano is so excited to
have solved the problem

264
00:12:17,570 --> 00:12:20,390
that stumped the best mathematicians
for thousands of years,

265
00:12:20,390 --> 00:12:22,280
he wants to publish it.

266
00:12:22,280 --> 00:12:23,210
Unlike his peers,

267
00:12:23,210 --> 00:12:26,120
Cardano has no need to
keep the solution a secret.

268
00:12:26,120 --> 00:12:28,620
He makes his living
not as a mathematician,

269
00:12:28,620 --> 00:12:31,490
but as a physician and
famous intellectual.

270
00:12:31,490 --> 00:12:35,510
For him, the credit is more
valuable than the secret.

271
00:12:35,510 --> 00:12:39,100
The only problem is the
oath he swore to Tartaglia

272
00:12:39,100 --> 00:12:41,460
who won't let him break it.

273
00:12:41,460 --> 00:12:43,730
And you might think this
would be the end of it.

274
00:12:43,730 --> 00:12:47,790
But in 1542, Cardano travels to Bologna

275
00:12:47,790 --> 00:12:49,650
and there he visits a mathematician

276
00:12:49,650 --> 00:12:51,780
who just happens to be the son-in-law

277
00:12:51,780 --> 00:12:55,700
of one Scipione del Ferro,
the man who on his deathbed,

278
00:12:55,700 --> 00:12:59,373
gave the solution to the
depressed cubic to Antonio Fior.

279
00:12:59,373 --> 00:13:02,750
Cardano finds the solution
in del Ferro's old notebook,

280
00:13:02,750 --> 00:13:04,840
which is shared with him during the visit.

281
00:13:04,840 --> 00:13:08,020
This solution predates
Tartaglia's by decades.

282
00:13:08,020 --> 00:13:09,750
So now, as Cardano sees it,

283
00:13:09,750 --> 00:13:11,960
he can publish the full
solution to the cubic

284
00:13:11,960 --> 00:13:15,500
without violating his oath to Tartaglia.

285
00:13:15,500 --> 00:13:16,470
Three years later,

286
00:13:16,470 --> 00:13:19,430
Cardano publishes "Ars
Magna," The Great Art,

287
00:13:19,430 --> 00:13:21,897
an updated compendium of mathematics.

288
00:13:21,897 --> 00:13:25,027
"Written in five years, may
it last for five hundred."

289
00:13:25,960 --> 00:13:28,830
Cardano writes a chapter
with a unique geometric proof

290
00:13:28,830 --> 00:13:32,250
for each of the 13 arrangements
of the cubic equation.

291
00:13:32,250 --> 00:13:33,280
Although he acknowledges

292
00:13:33,280 --> 00:13:36,590
the contributions of
Tartaglia, del Ferro and Fior,

293
00:13:36,590 --> 00:13:39,950
Tartaglia is displeased, to say the least.

294
00:13:39,950 --> 00:13:41,830
He writes insulting letters to Cardano,

295
00:13:41,830 --> 00:13:45,250
and CC's a good fraction of
the mathematics community.

296
00:13:45,250 --> 00:13:46,320
And he has a point.

297
00:13:46,320 --> 00:13:48,590
To this day, the general
solution to the cubic

298
00:13:48,590 --> 00:13:51,780
is often called Cardano's method.

299
00:13:51,780 --> 00:13:54,900
But "Ars Magna" is a
phenomenal achievement.

300
00:13:54,900 --> 00:13:59,540
It pushes geometrical reasoning
to its very breaking point.

301
00:13:59,540 --> 00:14:01,010
Literally.

302
00:14:01,010 --> 00:14:03,070
While Cardano is writing "Ars Magna "

303
00:14:03,070 --> 00:14:05,170
he comes across some cubic equations

304
00:14:05,170 --> 00:14:08,270
that can't easily be
solved in the usual way,

305
00:14:08,270 --> 00:14:11,910
like x cubed equals 15x plus four.

306
00:14:11,910 --> 00:14:14,580
Plugging this into the
algorithm yields a solution

307
00:14:14,580 --> 00:14:17,890
that contains the square
roots of negative numbers.

308
00:14:17,890 --> 00:14:20,220
Cardano asks Tartaglia about the case,

309
00:14:20,220 --> 00:14:22,270
but he evades and implies Cardano

310
00:14:22,270 --> 00:14:25,450
is just not clever enough
to use his formula properly.

311
00:14:25,450 --> 00:14:28,923
The reality is Tartaglia has
no idea what to do either.

312
00:14:30,120 --> 00:14:32,820
Cardano walks back through
the geometric derivation

313
00:14:32,820 --> 00:14:36,950
of a similar problem to see
exactly what goes wrong.

314
00:14:36,950 --> 00:14:40,690
While the 3D cube slicing and
rearrangement works just fine,

315
00:14:40,690 --> 00:14:43,360
the final quadratic
completing the square step

316
00:14:43,360 --> 00:14:46,150
leads to a geometric paradox.

317
00:14:46,150 --> 00:14:50,530
Cardano finds part of a square
that must have an area of 30,

318
00:14:50,530 --> 00:14:53,660
but also sides of length five.

319
00:14:53,660 --> 00:14:56,600
Since the full square has an area of 25,

320
00:14:56,600 --> 00:14:57,940
to complete the square,

321
00:14:57,940 --> 00:15:02,460
Cardano has to somehow add negative area.

322
00:15:02,460 --> 00:15:05,240
That is where the square
roots of negatives come from,

323
00:15:05,240 --> 00:15:08,520
the idea of negative area.

324
00:15:08,520 --> 00:15:09,730
Now, this isn't the first time

325
00:15:09,730 --> 00:15:12,150
square roots of negatives
show up in mathematics.

326
00:15:12,150 --> 00:15:15,670
In fact, earlier in "Ars
Magnae" is this problem.

327
00:15:15,670 --> 00:15:19,960
Find two numbers that add
to 10 and multiply to 40.

328
00:15:19,960 --> 00:15:22,500
You can combine these
equations into the quadratic

329
00:15:22,500 --> 00:15:25,550
X squared plus 40 equals 10 X.

330
00:15:25,550 --> 00:15:28,130
But if you plug this into
the quadratic formula,

331
00:15:28,130 --> 00:15:31,830
the solutions contain the
square roots of negatives.

332
00:15:31,830 --> 00:15:35,630
The obvious conclusion is
that a solution doesn't exist,

333
00:15:35,630 --> 00:15:38,370
which you can verify by looking
at the original problem.

334
00:15:38,370 --> 00:15:40,330
There are no two real numbers,

335
00:15:40,330 --> 00:15:42,823
which add to 10 and multiply to 40.

336
00:15:43,660 --> 00:15:45,840
So mathematicians understood

337
00:15:45,840 --> 00:15:47,520
square roots of negative numbers

338
00:15:47,520 --> 00:15:51,310
were maths way of telling
you there is no solution.

339
00:15:51,310 --> 00:15:54,280
But this cubic equation is different.

340
00:15:54,280 --> 00:15:55,710
With the little guessing and checking,

341
00:15:55,710 --> 00:15:59,700
you can find that x
equals four is a solution.

342
00:15:59,700 --> 00:16:02,830
So why doesn't the approach
that works for all other cubics

343
00:16:02,830 --> 00:16:06,520
find the perfectly reasonable
solution to this one?

344
00:16:06,520 --> 00:16:07,970
Unable to see a way forward,

345
00:16:07,970 --> 00:16:10,520
Cardano avoids this case in "Ars Magna"

346
00:16:10,520 --> 00:16:12,930
saying the idea of the
square root of negatives

347
00:16:12,930 --> 00:16:15,363
"is as subtle as it is useless".

348
00:16:16,910 --> 00:16:19,350
But around 10 years later,
the Italian engineer

349
00:16:19,350 --> 00:16:22,840
Rafael Bombelli picks up
where Cardano left off.

350
00:16:22,840 --> 00:16:24,650
Undeterred by the square
roots of negatives

351
00:16:24,650 --> 00:16:26,870
and the impossible geometry they imply,

352
00:16:26,870 --> 00:16:30,520
he wants to find a way through
the mess to the solution.

353
00:16:30,520 --> 00:16:32,360
Observing that the
square root of a negative

354
00:16:32,360 --> 00:16:35,370
"cannot be called either
positive or negative",

355
00:16:35,370 --> 00:16:39,100
he lets it be its own new type of number.

356
00:16:39,100 --> 00:16:41,670
Bombelli assumes the two
terms in Cardano's solution

357
00:16:41,670 --> 00:16:43,920
can be represented as some combination

358
00:16:43,920 --> 00:16:46,590
of an ordinary number and
this new type of number,

359
00:16:46,590 --> 00:16:49,130
which involves the square
root of negative one.

360
00:16:49,130 --> 00:16:51,350
And this way, Bombelli figures out

361
00:16:51,350 --> 00:16:53,900
that the two cube roots
in Cardano's equation

362
00:16:53,900 --> 00:16:55,110
are equivalent to two

363
00:16:55,110 --> 00:16:57,520
plus or minus the square
root of negative one.

364
00:16:57,520 --> 00:17:00,060
So when he takes the final
step and adds them together,

365
00:17:00,060 --> 00:17:01,520
the square roots cancel out,

366
00:17:01,520 --> 00:17:04,430
leaving the correct answer, four.

367
00:17:04,430 --> 00:17:07,080
This feels nothing short of miraculous.

368
00:17:07,080 --> 00:17:09,010
Cardano's method does work,

369
00:17:09,010 --> 00:17:11,370
but you have to abandon
the geometric proof

370
00:17:11,370 --> 00:17:13,960
that generated it in the first place.

371
00:17:13,960 --> 00:17:16,930
Negative areas, which
make no sense in reality,

372
00:17:16,930 --> 00:17:19,350
must exist as an intermediate step

373
00:17:19,350 --> 00:17:21,450
on the way to the solution.

374
00:17:21,450 --> 00:17:25,030
Over the next hundred years,
modern mathematics takes shape.

375
00:17:25,030 --> 00:17:27,200
In the 1600s, Francois Viete

376
00:17:27,200 --> 00:17:30,440
introduces the modern
symbolic notation for algebra,

377
00:17:30,440 --> 00:17:32,130
ending the millennia-long tradition

378
00:17:32,130 --> 00:17:35,450
of math problems as drawings
and wordy descriptions.

379
00:17:35,450 --> 00:17:39,110
Geometry is no longer the source of truth.

380
00:17:39,110 --> 00:17:40,870
Rene Descartes makes heavy use

381
00:17:40,870 --> 00:17:42,410
of the square roots of negatives,

382
00:17:42,410 --> 00:17:44,700
popularizing them as a result.

383
00:17:44,700 --> 00:17:46,690
And while he recognizes their utility,

384
00:17:46,690 --> 00:17:50,330
he calls them imaginary
numbers, a name that sticks,

385
00:17:50,330 --> 00:17:52,740
which is why Euler later
introduces the letter i

386
00:17:52,740 --> 00:17:55,330
to represent the square
root of negative one.

387
00:17:55,330 --> 00:17:57,230
When combined with regular numbers,

388
00:17:57,230 --> 00:17:59,900
they form complex numbers.

389
00:17:59,900 --> 00:18:02,670
The cubic led to the
invention of these new numbers

390
00:18:02,670 --> 00:18:05,830
and liberated algebra from geometry.

391
00:18:05,830 --> 00:18:06,950
By letting go

392
00:18:06,950 --> 00:18:09,410
of what seems like the best
description of reality,

393
00:18:09,410 --> 00:18:12,060
the geometry you can see and touch,

394
00:18:12,060 --> 00:18:14,810
you get a much more powerful
and complete mathematics

395
00:18:14,810 --> 00:18:17,130
that can solve real problems.

396
00:18:17,130 --> 00:18:20,770
And it turns out the cubic
is just the beginning.

397
00:18:20,770 --> 00:18:24,950
In 1925, Erwin Schrödinger is
searching for a wave equation

398
00:18:24,950 --> 00:18:27,410
that governs the behavior
of quantum particles

399
00:18:27,410 --> 00:18:28,750
building on de Broglie's insight

400
00:18:28,750 --> 00:18:31,190
that matter consists of waves.

401
00:18:31,190 --> 00:18:33,500
He comes up with one of the most important

402
00:18:33,500 --> 00:18:35,960
and famous equations in all of physics,

403
00:18:35,960 --> 00:18:37,770
the Schrödinger equation.

404
00:18:37,770 --> 00:18:40,770
And featured prominently within it is i,

405
00:18:40,770 --> 00:18:43,220
the square root of negative one.

406
00:18:43,220 --> 00:18:44,890
While mathematicians have grown accustomed

407
00:18:44,890 --> 00:18:47,740
to imaginary numbers, physicists have not

408
00:18:47,740 --> 00:18:49,560
and are uncomfortable seeing it show up

409
00:18:49,560 --> 00:18:51,500
in such a fundamental theory.

410
00:18:51,500 --> 00:18:53,277
Schrödinger himself writes

411
00:18:53,277 --> 00:18:54,690
"What is unpleasant here,

412
00:18:54,690 --> 00:18:57,370
and indeed directly to be objected to,

413
00:18:57,370 --> 00:18:59,640
is the use of complex numbers.

414
00:18:59,640 --> 00:19:01,100
The wave function Psi

415
00:19:01,100 --> 00:19:04,760
is surely fundamentally a real function."

416
00:19:04,760 --> 00:19:06,740
This seems like a fair objection,

417
00:19:06,740 --> 00:19:08,730
so why does an imaginary number

418
00:19:08,730 --> 00:19:11,010
that first appeared in
the solution to the cubic

419
00:19:11,010 --> 00:19:13,560
turn up in fundamental physics?

420
00:19:13,560 --> 00:19:16,490
Well, it's because of
some unique properties

421
00:19:16,490 --> 00:19:18,510
of imaginary numbers.

422
00:19:18,510 --> 00:19:22,120
Imaginary numbers exist on
a dimension perpendicular

423
00:19:22,120 --> 00:19:23,920
to the real number line.

424
00:19:23,920 --> 00:19:27,160
Together, they form the complex plane.

425
00:19:27,160 --> 00:19:30,800
Watch what happens when we
repeatedly multiply by i.

426
00:19:30,800 --> 00:19:32,330
Starting with one.

427
00:19:32,330 --> 00:19:34,810
One times i is i,

428
00:19:34,810 --> 00:19:38,100
i times i is negative one, by definition.

429
00:19:38,100 --> 00:19:41,010
Negative one times i is negative i,

430
00:19:41,010 --> 00:19:43,630
and negative i times i is one.

431
00:19:43,630 --> 00:19:45,050
We've come back to where we started,

432
00:19:45,050 --> 00:19:46,740
and if we keep multiplying by i,

433
00:19:46,740 --> 00:19:49,250
the point will keep rotating around.

434
00:19:49,250 --> 00:19:51,300
So when you're multiplying by i,

435
00:19:51,300 --> 00:19:53,830
what you're really doing is rotating

436
00:19:53,830 --> 00:19:56,800
by 90 degrees in the complex plane.

437
00:19:56,800 --> 00:20:00,300
Now, there is a function that
repeatedly multiplies by i

438
00:20:00,300 --> 00:20:02,420
as you go down the X-axis.

439
00:20:02,420 --> 00:20:05,460
And that is e to the ix.

440
00:20:05,460 --> 00:20:08,560
It creates a spiral by
essentially spreading out

441
00:20:08,560 --> 00:20:12,070
these rotations all along the X-axis.

442
00:20:12,070 --> 00:20:14,030
If you look at the real
part of the spiral,

443
00:20:14,030 --> 00:20:15,630
it's a cosine wave.

444
00:20:15,630 --> 00:20:19,120
And if you look at the imaginary
part, it's a sine wave.

445
00:20:19,120 --> 00:20:22,160
The two quintessential
functions that describe waves

446
00:20:22,160 --> 00:20:25,133
are both contained in e to the ix.

447
00:20:26,210 --> 00:20:28,770
So when Schrodinger goes to
write down a wave equation,

448
00:20:28,770 --> 00:20:31,750
he naturally assumes that
the solutions to his equation

449
00:20:31,750 --> 00:20:33,860
will look something like e to the ix,

450
00:20:33,860 --> 00:20:37,420
specifically e to the ikx minus omega t.

451
00:20:37,420 --> 00:20:40,450
You might wonder why he
would use that formulation

452
00:20:40,450 --> 00:20:42,670
and not just a simple sine wave,

453
00:20:42,670 --> 00:20:45,440
but the exponential has
some useful properties.

454
00:20:45,440 --> 00:20:48,890
If you take the derivative with
respect to position or time,

455
00:20:48,890 --> 00:20:50,560
that derivative is proportional

456
00:20:50,560 --> 00:20:52,790
to the original function itself.

457
00:20:52,790 --> 00:20:55,610
And that's not true if
you use the sine function

458
00:20:55,610 --> 00:20:57,760
whose derivative is cosine.

459
00:20:57,760 --> 00:21:00,640
Plus, since the Schrodinger
equation is linear,

460
00:21:00,640 --> 00:21:03,390
you can add together an
arbitrary number of solutions

461
00:21:03,390 --> 00:21:07,310
of this form, creating any
sort of wave shape you like,

462
00:21:07,310 --> 00:21:10,670
and it too, will be a solution
to Schrodinger's equation.

463
00:21:10,670 --> 00:21:13,437
The physicist Freeman Dyson later writes,

464
00:21:13,437 --> 00:21:15,500
"Schrödinger put the
square root of minus one

465
00:21:15,500 --> 00:21:18,810
into the equation, and
suddenly it made sense.

466
00:21:18,810 --> 00:21:21,190
Suddenly it became a wave equation

467
00:21:21,190 --> 00:21:23,340
instead of a heat conduction equation.

468
00:21:23,340 --> 00:21:25,640
And Schrodinger found to his delight

469
00:21:25,640 --> 00:21:27,160
that the equation has solutions

470
00:21:27,160 --> 00:21:29,310
corresponding to the quantized orbits

471
00:21:29,310 --> 00:21:31,560
in the Bohr model of the atom.

472
00:21:31,560 --> 00:21:33,640
It turns out that the Schrodinger equation

473
00:21:33,640 --> 00:21:36,130
describes correctly everything we know

474
00:21:36,130 --> 00:21:38,290
about the behavior of atoms.

475
00:21:38,290 --> 00:21:42,600
It is the basis of all of
chemistry and most of physics.

476
00:21:42,600 --> 00:21:44,200
And that square root of minus one

477
00:21:44,200 --> 00:21:47,600
means that nature works
with complex numbers

478
00:21:47,600 --> 00:21:50,340
and not with real numbers.

479
00:21:50,340 --> 00:21:53,520
This discovery came as
a complete surprise,

480
00:21:53,520 --> 00:21:56,980
to Schrodinger as well
as to everybody else."

481
